I have [asked](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/27729734/styling-alternating-lines-in-atom-editor) this on Stack overflow but it seems to be harder than I thought.

Problem: I wanted to make the odd lines a different colour so that when I set soft line wraps I can see clearly that it is one line split over 2 or 3 without having to focus on the dots in the gutter.

Attempt to fix: In my style.less I tried adding:

.editor .line:nth-child(2n){
  background-color:#292929;
}

Then I tried:
.editor .line[data-screen-row]:nth-child(2n) {
  background-color:#292929;
}

Here is the screen shot in the SO post:
![atom_line_mess](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/775993/5596890/e0cb89a2-92db-11e4-9aae-20ab755224c8.png)

The issue: The order of the lines is not related to the actual order in the document so this was not consistent. I don't know why the data-screen-row didn't work but it still did not highlight correctly.

I am currently looking into plugins but I can not figure out how to effect these line generators (if someone can tell me where to look I can work on a plugin.

I think it would need something like for example an odd and even class on the lines (It would also need to know if the line is wrapped and make it even or odd based on the original document and not the display in the DOM.

Is there a way to do this with just CSS/LESS that I missed?

Another issue I noticed is that when I add the background colour to the lines highlighting does not work, It would also be nice to add a way to control the depth so advice about how that would work would also be cool.

Thanks in advance for any advice you can offer.
